gmd:abstract.gco:CharacterString: The National Data Buoy Center (NDBC) established the Coastal-Marine Automated Network (C-MAN) for the National Weather Service in the early 1980's. NDBC has installed approximately 50 C-MAN stations on lighthouses, at capes and beaches, on near shore islands, and on offshore platforms. NDBC has also deployed over 100 moored (a.k.a., weather) buoys in coastal and offshore waters from the western Atlantic to the Pacific Ocean around Hawaii, and from the Bering Sea to the South Pacific. C-MAN and moored buoy data typically include barometric pressure, wind direction, speed and gust, and air temperature; however, some C-MAN stations are equipped to also measure seawater temperature, water level, waves, and relative humidity. Moored buoys measure wave energy spectra from which NDBC derives significant wave height, dominant wave period, and average wave period. In addition, many moored buoys measure the direction of wave propagation. In collaboration, NDBC and the National Centers for Environmental Information (NCEI) -- formerly the National Oceanographic Data Center (NODC) -- are archiving these data from C-MAN and moored buoys. This collection is part of the collaboration and it contains both NODC F291 and netCDF (version 4) files with data collected from February 1970 through the present day.

gmd:purpose.gco:CharacterString: The purpose of collecting this data set is to respond to the need for recorded continuous meteorological and oceanographic observations in the US coastal areas.

gmd:statement.gco:CharacterString: The data were produced by the National Data Buoy Center (NDBC) and are archived at the NOAA National Centers for Environmental Information (NCEI). The original data before January 2011 were in the F291 format and have been converted into NetCDF by NCEI.

gmd:description.gco:CharacterString: The original data in the F291 format prior to January 2011 have been converted to NetCDF by using the F291NC program version 0.4.1. F291NC was developed by NCEI, utilizing information from the original F291 format specification to map fields to the NCEI TimeSeries Orthogonal v2.0 NetCDF Template. The software extracted data from the fields in each original F291 file and copied those data to fields into a corresponding NetCDF file. The best effort was made to take into account the requirements and limitations of the F291 format, such that the resulting NetCDF file would represent the original data as closely as possible, except for the ten minute averages of wind direction and wind speed appearing in Record Type J. The ten minute averages are named as FIRST, SECOND, ..., and SIXTH. After ten minutes, the FIRST AVERAGE of the prior F291 record appears as the SECOND AVERAGE of the current F291 record, SECOND AVERAGE as THIRD AVERAGE, up to FIFTH AVERAGE as SIXTH AVERAGE. This shift of ten minute averages introduces redundant data points. Following how the National Data Buoy Center stores the ten minute averages in their NetCDF files in and after January 2011, we filtered out redundant data and placed the ten minute averages of wind speed and wind direction to NetCDF arrays continuous_wind_speed and continuous_wind_direction, respectively. This improvement not only reduces the size of resulting NetCDF files but also provides much more convenient way to access the averages. Processing messages, warnings and errors were captured to log files, one per original F291 data file.

gmd:measureDescription.gco:CharacterString: The Data Stewardship Maturity Matrix (DSMM) is a unified framework that defines criteria for each of nine components based on measurable practices, which can be used to apply a progressive, 6-level rating to an individual dataset, representing stewardship maturity stages rated as Not Assessed or Not Available (Level 0), adHoc (Level 1), minimum (Level 2), intermediate (Level 3), advanced (Level 4), and optimal (Level 5).

gmd:description.gco:CharacterString: NOAA created the National Centers for Environmental Information (NCEI) by merging NOAA's National Climatic Data Center (NCDC), National Geophysical Data Center (NGDC), and National Oceanographic Data Center (NODC), including the National Coastal Data Development Center (NCDDC), per the Consolidated and Further Continuing Appropriations Act, 2015, Public Law 113-235. NCEI launched publicly on April 22, 2015.
